Antes de empezar a analizar el dataset la variable year_month se va a transformar para que los algoritmos puedan utilizarlo.

El atributo year_month incluye el a√±o y mes en los que la canci√≥n estuvo en el Gaon chart. De estos valores se pueden extraer m√∫ltiples features:

  • N√∫mero de meses que la canci√≥n estuvo en Gaon.
  • Primer mes y a√±o en el que la canci√≥n apareci√≥ en el chart.

In [ ]:
df['times_in_chart'] = df.year_month.str.count("-") + 1 # n√∫mero de veces que aparece en el chart
In [ ]:
year_month_first_time = df.year_month.str.split("-").str[0] # first year and month in chart
year_month_first_time = pd.to_datetime(year_month_first_time, format='%Y%m') # convert to pandas datetime
df['first_time_in_chart_date'] = year_month_first_time

df['first_time_in_chart_year'] = year_month_first_time.dt.year
df['first_time_in_chart_month'] = year_month_first_time.dt.month
df['first_time_in_chart_quarter'] = year_month_first_time.dt.quarter
df['first_time_in_chart_period'] = "other"  # summer (June to August), holiday (November to January)
df.loc[(df.first_time_in_chart_month >= 6) & (df.first_time_in_chart_month <= 8), "first_time_in_chart_period"] = "summer"
df.loc[(df.first_time_in_chart_month >= 11) & (df.first_time_in_chart_month <= 12) | (df.first_time_in_chart_month == 1), "first_time_in_chart_period"] = "holiday"

# Se corrigen los tipos de los datos que no sean correctos
def fix_column_types(df, label=True):
    fix_cat_columns = ["producer", "distributor", "album_type", "first_time_in_chart_period", 
                    "is_collab", "explicit", "is_ost", "for_reality_tvshow"]
    if label is True:
        fix_cat_columns += ['is_popular']
    for c in fix_cat_columns:
        df[c] = df[c].astype('category')
        df[c] = df[c].cat.remove_unused_categories()

En el campo duration_ms se observan valores raros al tener un valor m√≠nimo de 3 segundos. Se ordenan las canciones por su duraci√≥n de forma ascendente y se comprueban los valores para saber si son v√°lidos.

Tras investigar se conoce que en Spotify la primera canci√≥n no est√° de manera correcta y se borra. El resto de canciones que no duran ni un minuto se han comprobado, y como bien dice el t√≠tulo corresponden a canciones que se suelen utilizar al principio (intro) o al final (outro) de los √°lbumes. Este tipo de canciones suelen ser m√°s cortas y sirven de introducci√≥n por lo que son correctas.

import spotipy
from spotipy.oauth2 import SpotifyClientCredentials

SPOTIPY_CLIENT_ID='xxxxxxx'
SPOTIPY_CLIENT_SECRET='xxxxxxx'

cut_off = 600

auth_manager = SpotifyClientCredentials(client_id=SPOTIPY_CLIENT_ID, 
                                        client_secret=SPOTIPY_CLIENT_SECRET)
sp = spotipy.Spotify(auth_manager=auth_manager)

songs_to_fix = df.loc[df.tempo > cut_off, "spotify_uri"]
songs_to_fix_indexes = songs_to_fix.index

response = sp.audio_features(tracks=songs_to_fix.to_list())
for r,i in zip(response, songs_to_fix_indexes):
  df.loc[i, "tempo"] = r['tempo']

Problema balanceado¶

Una vez analizados estos atributos se descartan, ya que como se ha indicado previamente tres de ellos conllevan data leakage y el otro (times_in_chart) no pertenece al problema que se quiere resolver.

In [ ]:
df.drop(['num_times_top_10', 'num_times_top_5', 'num_times_top_1', 'times_in_chart'], axis=1, inplace=True)

Se comprueba si la clase is_popular est√° balanceada. No est√° balanceada pero la diferencia es m√≠nima, por lo que en un principio se considera como problema balanceado. En futuro se podr√≠an utilizar algoritmos (por ejemplo, SMOTE) para balancear los datos.

def draw_graphs(df, graph='hist', width=15, height=15, cols=1, ylabel='count', **kwargs):
  # Dibujar los distintos tipos de gr√°ficos 

    fig = plt.figure(1, (width, height))
    rows = len(df.describe().columns)

    i = 1

    for col in df.describe().columns:
        ax = plt.subplot(rows, cols, i)
        if graph=="hist":
            sns.histplot(data=df, x=col, kde=True)
        elif graph == "bar":
            order = None
            if kwargs.get("ordered", None):
                order = df[col].value_counts().index
            ax = sns.countplot(x=col, data=df, color=kwargs.get("color", 'steelblue'), 
                               order = order, hue=kwargs.get("hue", None))

            # ax.bar(df[col].value_counts().index, df[col].value_counts().values)
            if kwargs.get("korean_ticks", None):
                plt.xticks(fontproperties=fontprop, 
                           fontsize=12, rotation=90)
        elif graph == "outliers":
            ax.boxplot(df[col], vert=False)
        
        elif graph == "boxplot":
            sns.boxplot(x=kwargs.get("train_y", None), y=col, data=df)
            
        elif graph == "scatterplot":
            sns.scatterplot(data=df, x=kwargs.get("x",None), y=col)

        ax.set_xlabel(col, fontproperties=fontprop)
        ax.set_ylabel(ylabel, fontproperties=fontprop)

        i += 1

        plt.tight_layout()

Se obtienen los outliers de loudness y speechiness para analizarlos. Se analizan los valores m√°s bajos de loudness y los valores m√°s altos de speechiness.

In [ ]:
def get_outliers(train_X, c):
    # Values < Q1-1.5*IQR or > Q3+1.5*IQR are treated as outliers

    Q1 = train_X[c].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = train_X[c].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower = Q1-1.5*IQR
    upper = Q3+1.5*IQR
    return IQR, lower, upper

Las canciones populares son más bailables y tienen más energía que las no populares¶

In [ ]:
# Contraste de hip√≥tesis de dos muestras sobre la diferencia de medias
features = ['danceability', 'energy']
for f in features:
    populares = train_X[train_y==1][f]
    no_populares = train_X[train_y==0][f]
    
    media_popular = populares.mean()
    media_no_popular = no_populares.mean()
    varianza_popular = populares.var()
    varianza_no_popular = no_populares.var()
    num_popular = len(populares)
    num_no_popular = len(no_populares)

    numerador = media_popular - media_no_popular
    denominador = np.sqrt((varianza_popular/num_popular) 
                          + (varianza_no_popular/num_no_popular))
    
    estadistico = numerador / denominador
    pvalue = stats.norm.sf(estadistico)
    
    print(f"Feature {f} -- estadistico {estadistico} -- pvalue {pvalue}")

Feature danceability -- estadistico 2.8999298956001263 -- pvalue 0.0018662306415185752
Feature energy -- estadistico 2.7047217502337237 -- pvalue 0.0034180812549466843

# Test Barlett varianzas iguales
years = [2010, 2013, 2016, 2019] # de tres en tres
data_by_year = []
features = ["danceability", "valence", "energy", "acousticness", "loudness"] 

for y in years:
    data_by_year.append(train_X[train_X["first_time_in_chart_year"] == y])

for f in features:
    stat, p = stats.bartlett(data_by_year[0][f], data_by_year[1][f], 
                             data_by_year[2][f], data_by_year[3][f])
    print(f"Feature {f} -- pValue {p}")

# Tukey multiple comparisons of means
filter_by_years = train_X[train_X['first_time_in_chart_year'].isin(years)]

for f in features:
    values = filter_by_years[f]
    groups = filter_by_years['first_time_in_chart_year']
    
    m_comp = pairwise_tukeyhsd(endog=values, groups=groups, alpha=0.05)
    print("Feature ", f)
    print(m_comp)
    print()
    print()

def backup(train_X, train_y, test_X, test_y):
    train_X.to_csv(f"{OUTPUT_FOLDER}train_X_temporal.csv", sep=";", index=False)
    train_y.to_csv(f"{OUTPUT_FOLDER}train_y_temporal.csv", sep=";", index=False)

    test_X.to_csv(f"{OUTPUT_FOLDER}test_X_temporal.csv", sep=";", index=False)
    test_y.to_csv(f"{OUTPUT_FOLDER}test_y_temporal.csv", sep=";", index=False)

    
def restore():
    train_X = pd.read_csv(f"{OUTPUT_FOLDER}train_X_temporal.csv", sep=";")
    train_y = pd.read_csv(f"{OUTPUT_FOLDER}train_y_temporal.csv", sep=";")

    test_X = pd.read_csv(f"{OUTPUT_FOLDER}test_X_temporal.csv", sep=";")
    test_y = pd.read_csv(f"{OUTPUT_FOLDER}test_y_temporal.csv", sep=";")
    
    return train_X, train_y, test_X, test_y

def group_low_categories(df_train, df_test, column, upper):
    categories_to_change = df_train[column].value_counts()[(df_train[column].value_counts(
        normalize=True) < upper)].index.to_list()
    df_train.loc[df_train[column].isin(categories_to_change), column] = "other"
    column_train_values = df_train[column].value_counts().index
    df_test.loc[~df_test[column].isin(column_train_values), column] = "other"

A√±adir atributo "artist has a previous popular song"

In [ ]:
class ArtistHasPreviousPopular(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    """Takes in dataframe and creates new features """

    def __init__(self, binary_features, add=True):
        self.add = add
        self.feature_name = "artist_before_popular" # feature name
        self.first_time_popular = None # datos transformados para poder a√±adir el campo
        self.desdoblada = None 
        self.binary_features = binary_features # se pasa por referencia, 
                                               # si el campo se a√±ade se actualiza        
   
    def transform(self, X, y=None):
        """The workhorse of this feature extractor"""
        if self.add is False:
            if self.feature_name in self.binary_features:
                self.binary_features.remove(self.feature_name)
            return X
        
        if self.first_time_popular is None:
            print("Fit the train data first!")
            return
        
        self.desdoblar(X, y)
                    
        # transforming train or test
        self.first_time_popular.apply(lambda row: self.artist_before_popular_lambda(
            row, self.desdoblada),axis=1)

        X = X.copy()
        X[self.feature_name] = 0
        X.loc[self.desdoblada[
            self.desdoblada[self.feature_name] == 1].orig_index, self.feature_name] = 1
        
        # add feature to binary feature list
        if self.feature_name not in self.binary_features:
            self.binary_features.append(self.feature_name)
       
        return X

    def artist_before_popular_lambda(self, row, df):
        df.loc[(df.singer_id == row.singer_id) & (
               (df.first_time_in_chart_year > row.first_time_in_chart_year) |
               ((df.first_time_in_chart_month > row.first_time_in_chart_month) & 
                (df.first_time_in_chart_year == row.first_time_in_chart_year))), self.feature_name] = 1
        
    def desdoblar(self, X, y=None):
        if y is None:
            tmp_y = -1
        else:
            tmp_y = y.copy()
        
        # transforming 
        self.desdoblada = X.copy()
        self.desdoblada['orig_index'] = X.index
        self.desdoblada = self.desdoblada[['singer_id', 'first_time_in_chart_year', 'first_time_in_chart_month', 'orig_index']]
        self.desdoblada['popular'] = tmp_y

        # desdoblar cada singer id para que cada uno est√© en una fila
        b = pd.DataFrame(self.desdoblada.singer_id.str.split('-sep-').tolist(), index=[
            self.desdoblada.first_time_in_chart_year, self.desdoblada.first_time_in_chart_month,
            self.desdoblada.popular, self.desdoblada.orig_index]).stack()
        b = b.reset_index()[[0, 'first_time_in_chart_year', 'first_time_in_chart_month','popular', 'orig_index']] 
        b.columns = ['singer_id', 'first_time_in_chart_year', 'first_time_in_chart_month', 'popular', 'orig_index']
        self.desdoblada = b

    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        """Returns `self` unless something different happens in train and test"""
        if self.add is False:
            # check if the name of the feature is in the list and delete it if so
            if self.feature_name in self.binary_features:
                self.binary_features.remove(self.feature_name)
            return self
        
        self.desdoblar(X, y)

        # solo con train
        self.first_time_popular = self.desdoblada.sort_values(['first_time_in_chart_year', 
                                                     'first_time_in_chart_month'], 
                                                    ascending=True)
        self.first_time_popular = self.first_time_popular[(self.first_time_popular.popular == 1)].drop_duplicates(
            'singer_id')
        return self

class PassThrough(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    """Takes in dataframe and creates new features """    
   
    def transform(self, X, y=None):
        """The workhorse of this feature extractor"""
        return X

    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        return self
In [ ]:
scoring = ["accuracy", "precision", "recall", "f1"]
def define_pipeline(categorical_pipeline='default', binary_pipeline=None, 
                    numerical_pipeline='default', model=None, artist_feature=True):
    numeric_features_aux = numeric_features
    binary_features_aux = binary_features
    categorical_features_aux = categorical_features

    # Categorical features
    if not categorical_pipeline or categorical_pipeline == "remove": 
        categorical_transformer = Pipeline([
                ('cat_pass', PassThrough()),
            ])
    elif categorical_pipeline == 'default':
        # default
        categorical_transformer = Pipeline([
            ('one_hot_encoder', OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore')),
        ])
    else:
        categorical_transformer = categorical_pipeline
        
    if categorical_pipeline == 'remove':
        categorical_features_aux = []

    # Numerical features
    if not numerical_pipeline or numerical_pipeline == 'remove':
        numerical_transformer = Pipeline([
                ('num_pass', PassThrough()),
            ])
    elif numerical_pipeline == "default":
        # default
        numerical_transformer = Pipeline([
            ('scaler', StandardScaler()),
        ])
    else:
        numerical_transformer = numerical_pipeline
        
    if numerical_pipeline == 'remove':
        numerical_features_aux = []
        
    # Binary features
    if not binary_pipeline or binary_pipeline == "remove":
        binary_transformer =  Pipeline([
                ('pass', PassThrough()),
            ])
    else:
        binary_transformer =  binary_pipeline
    
    if binary_pipeline == 'remove':
        binary_features_aux = []

    preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
        transformers=[
            ('num', numerical_transformer, numeric_features_aux),
            ('binary', binary_transformer, binary_features_aux),
            ('cat', categorical_transformer, categorical_features_aux)])
    
    clf_preprocess = Pipeline(steps=[ 
                          ('add_feature_previous_popular', ArtistHasPreviousPopular(binary_features, add=artist_feature)),
                          ('preprocessor', preprocessor)])

    if model is not None:
        clf = Pipeline(steps = [
                              ('preprocess', clf_preprocess),  
                              ('classifier', model)])
    else:
        clf = clf_preprocess
        
    return clf
    
def define_pipeline_and_optimize(categorical_pipeline='default', binary_pipeline=None, 
                                 numerical_pipeline='default', model_grid_values={}, 
                                 custom_grid_values={}, model=None, artist_feature=True):
    
    grid_values = {**model_grid_values, **custom_grid_values}
    
    clf = define_pipeline(categorical_pipeline, binary_pipeline, numerical_pipeline, 
                          model, artist_feature)
    
    # optimize precision and monitor the scoring
    best = GridSearchCV(clf, grid_values, cv=CV_SPLITS, refit='precision', scoring=scoring, 
                        return_train_score=True)
    best.fit(train_X, train_y)
    
    # print metrics
    print(best.best_params_)
    best_scores = pd.DataFrame(best.cv_results_)
    for k,v in best.best_params_.items():
        best_scores = best_scores[best_scores["param_" + k] == v]

    for s in scoring:
        print(f"{s}: %0.2f" % (best_scores["mean_test_" + s]))
        
    return best.best_estimator_
In [ ]:
def plot_learning_curves(pipeline, train_X, train_y, cv=CV_SPLITS, scoring='precision'):
    train_sizes, train_scores, valid_scores = learning_curve(pipeline, train_X, 
                                                         train_y, cv=cv, scoring=scoring)
    train_scores_mean = train_scores.mean(axis = 1)
    validation_scores_mean = valid_scores.mean(axis = 1)
    plt.plot(train_sizes, train_scores_mean, label = f'Training {scoring}')
    plt.plot(train_sizes, validation_scores_mean, label = f'Validation {scoring}')
    plt.ylabel(scoring, fontsize = 14)
    plt.xlabel('Training set size', fontsize = 14)
    plt.title('Learning curves for model', fontsize = 18, y = 1.03)
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

def cross_validation(clf, train_X, train_y, cv=CV_SPLITS):
    scoring = {'accuracy': 'accuracy',
           'precision': 'precision',
           'recall': 'recall',
           'f1':'f1'}
    scores = cross_validate(clf, train_X, train_y, cv=CV_SPLITS, 
                            scoring=scoring, n_jobs = -1)
    for k,v in scores.items():
        print(f"{k}: %0.2f (+/- %0.2f)" % (v.mean(), v.std() * 2))

5. Atributos numéricos + categóricos One Hot Encoding + new atribute + log/square root¶










Probar log y square root sin loudness (es negativo)











In [ ]:



     


class CustomTransformer(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    """Takes in dataframe and creates new features """

    def __init__(self, log=False, exclude=None):
        self.log = log
        self.square_root = (log == False)
        self.exclude = exclude # exclude the variable with negative values
        
    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        return self
       
    def transform(self, X, y=None):
        new = X.copy()
        if self.exclude:
            new.drop(self.exclude, axis=1, inplace=True)
            
        method = None

        if self.log is True:
            method = np.log1p
        elif self.square_root is True:
            method = np.sqrt
        if method:
            for c in new.columns:
                new[c] = method(new[c])
        return new

from sklearn.metrics import plot_confusion_matrix



     















In [ ]:



     


def fit_model_with_test(model, train_X, train_y, test_X, test_y):
    model.fit(train_X, train_y)
    predicted = model.predict(test_X)
    print(metrics.classification_report(test_y, predicted))
    disp = plot_confusion_matrix(model, test_X, test_y,
                                     cmap=plt.cm.Blues)
    print(disp.confusion_matrix)
    plt.grid(None)
    plt.show()

2. Atributos numéricos + Label Encoding¶










In [ ]:



     


class MultiColumnLabelEncoder(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    
    def __init__(self):
        self.mappings = {}
    
    def fit(self,X,y=None):
        for col in X.columns:
            col_dictionary = {}
            original_strings = X[col].value_counts().index
            numbers = X[col].astype('category').cat.codes.value_counts().index
            col_dictionary = dict(zip(original_strings, numbers))
            self.mappings[col] = col_dictionary
        return self

    def transform(self,X):
        X = X.copy()
    
        for col in X.columns:
            mapping_dict = self.mappings[col]

            strings_not_found = X[~X[col].isin(mapping_dict.keys())].index

            # map found values
            X.replace({col: mapping_dict}, inplace=True)
            
            # put most frequent value for not found strings
            keys_view = mapping_dict.keys()
            key_iterator = iter(keys_view)
            first_key = next(key_iterator)
            X.loc[strings_not_found, col] = first_key
        return X



     















In [ ]:
